contentDescription: Who doesn't want to live a long and healthy life? An American and Swedish study observed 650,000 people and found that those exercising regularly added years to their life.   These results weren't dependent on the participants' weight - meaning exercising regularly is important to everyone's long-term health.
Exercise has been shown to reduce your blood pressure for about 24 hours afterwards. Although the effect is only temporary, exercising daily can help maintain or reduce your blood pressure.

Exercise often gets lumped together regardless of intensity, but there is a difference in how your body responds. A study published in 2019 showed that those who participated in vigorous exercise had a lower risk of all-cause mortality than those who only participated in moderate-intensity exercise or less.
Did you really need another excuse to eat bananas? They truly are a superfood!

Although dried and tinned can still be considered servings of fruit, fresh is best! It's more filling and less likely to contain added sugars. If you can't get fresh, snap frozen fruit like berries are also a great option.

Instead of letting old bananas go to waste, peel it or chop it and store it in a container in your freezer. Then if you need a quick breakfast, you can make yourself a smoothie with milk of your choice, a sprinkle of cinnamon and a handful of nuts. Yum!
If you haven't had corn for a while, then consider this a sign to buy a few cobs. Eat it as a snack, put it on your dinner plate or chop it up in a salad.

Get those veggies into you. The aim is five servings a day, which can be tricky to fit in. Having a savoury breakfast with a serving of veggies means it's not too hard to spread the rest over lunch and dinner.
That's almost 50% of what you're squeezing onto your burger! Would you sprinkle two teaspoons of sugar onto a sausage?
Chicken teriyaki is a common and tasty lunch or dinner option, but would you sprinkle sugar on your chicken and rice at home? It's another hidden sugar that can catch you out!

Yep, that's right! Sugar can contribute to overall cardiovascular risk through a range of factors, including elevated heart rate, higher blood pressure and insulin resistance, just to name a few.   You can help reduce your risk of heart disease by saying no to a processed sugary snack, and go for a crunchy apple if you need that pick-me-up. ;)
Cutting back on salt can do wonderful things for your heart health. 3g/day should be the long term target for salt consumption. So throw away that salt shaker!
Salt is hidden in a lot of packaged food products. Check the 100g nutritional label on the back of the packaging to find out whether it's low in salt.

Salt may be a flavour enhancer, but you can get used to the taste of salt and constantly seek out saltier options. Be mindful of what high-salt foods are and try to pick a low-salt alternative. Add herbs and spices instead to boost the flavour in your food.
Legumes are a great nutritional choice! They are low GI, and full of vitamins and minerals. You can put them in your salad, make a taco mix or even a savoury mince on toast. Yum!

Exercise with a poor diet won't help you achieve your weight loss goals. It's really important to eat foods that are mostly unprocessed, such as veggies and fruit, and avoid consuming junk food on a regular basis.
Magnesium is critical for your body to stay healthy. It helps regulate muscle and nerve function, blood sugar levels and blood pressure. It also assists in making protein, bone, and even your DNA.

Here are three reasons why nuts can help reduce heart disease: 1. They contain good fats that help boost your good cholesterol. 2. The fibre in nuts helps reduce cholesterol reabsorption from the gut. 3. They have naturally low sodium and high potassium levels which help maintain a healthy blood pressure.

The high levels of monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats found in nuts may help enhance insulin sensitivity. They may help people with diabetes too. When nuts are added to carbohydrate-rich meals they slow down the overall digestion. Nuts help reduce the overall GI of someone's diet and therefore can help manage glucose levels in the body.

This is true! Dinner plates in the 1970s were 25cm in diameter and now they're up to 31cm. An easy way to help control your portions is to reduce your plate size. You eat with your eyes, so you naturally want to fill a larger plate.

Most low-fat diets encourage less than 37% of your total energy to come from fat. The Mediterranean diet is approximately 41% energy from good fats (monounsaturated and polyunsaturated). Add/swap good quality extra virgin olive oil, fish and unsalted nuts to your diet to introduce good fats.

Magnesium helps the body break down sugars and may reduce the risk of insulin resistance (an inability to process glucose). Scientists are currently investigating whether magnesium supplements might help control type 2 diabetes, but more research still needs to occur in this space.

When you have eaten carbohydrates or sweet foods, your body releases insulin to help process the sugar in your bloodstream and maintain a healthy level. The more sugar you eat, the more pressure is put on this system. After a while your body can become insulin-resistant, increasing your chance of developing type 2 diabetes.
Why not add mindfulness meditation or yoga to your day, even if it's just a couple of minutes. It can teach you to stay present which can help with pressing deadlines or just appreciating the day.
Did you know that several studies have found mindfulness meditation can improve sleep quality for people with sleep disturbances? If you have trouble sleeping, maybe give this a go.

A study from Ball State University showed that those who practised 10 minutes of mindfulness before listening to a 10-minute audiotape outperformed their counterparts who didn't participate in mindfulness prior. If you want to improve your verbal learning and memory, perhaps add a little mindfulness meditation to your day.

When experiencing heavy emotions, learning to be mindful can help you stay grounded. You get a clearer understanding of how to feel and better equipped to handle those emotions. Practice some breath-focused meditation to help you feel more in control of your emotions.

This is true! Scientists didn't know where the 'clock' was until they trialled removing a tiny part of a hamster brain called the suprachiasmatic nucleus. Humans have one too. It's a very tiny part of the brain inside the hypothalamus responsible for your circadian rhythm.

When your eyes see light, it sends signals to your body clock to keep it in sync with the environment. That's why when you fly overseas, your body clock may be out, but it quickly goes to reprogramming you to be in sync with the new environment.
When all light is removed, the body clock can't use any external signal to correct when it should be awake or sleep. Over time, the body continues to shift a little further out of rhythm.
Social jetlag is real! Just like changing time zones can affect your sleep patterns. If your bedtime and wake up time changes day to day, you're going to struggle with having enough quality sleep.

Your body clock is naturally regulated through your exposure to sunlight. The sun emits blue light, which tells your body that it's daytime. Many indoor lights and electronic devices also emit the same blue light and when used late at night, these lights can trick the brain into thinking it's daytime, disrupting the sleep cycle.

Although heredity plays a part in your risk of developing heart disease, tobacco use, poor diets, obesity, physical inactivity and excessive alcohol play a major part. What can you do to help reduce your risk?

Although short term stress is completely normal, the release of cortisol from the stress response increases blood pressure, cholesterol and triglyceride levels. Over time, this can lead to a higher risk of cardiovascular disease. Look after yourself, physically and mentally for a long, healthy life.

Research has found strong correlations between decreased heart function and ongoing stress such as work stress or bereavement. It's crucial to adopt effective stress management strategies to maintain good heart health. This may mean exercising daily, reading a book to relax and knowing that a few deep breaths can help.
Do you want to reduce your risk of type 2 diabetes? There's a lot you can do! Avoid sugary foods and drinks, eat more whole foods, exercise daily and maintain a healthy body weight.

Around 1.7 million Aussies currently have diabetes. This number includes all types of diabetes, but the most common is also the most preventable: type 2 diabetes.   Reducing the amount of processed foods and alcohol consumed, increasing physical activity, and maintaining a healthy body are great ways to reduce your risk of developing type 2 diabetes.
If diabetes is in your family or you eat a lot of processed foods, are fairly inactive or overweight, perhaps it's time to talk to your doctor.
Exercise works a bit like insulin to help manage blood sugar levels. Even if you don't have diabetes - prevention is better than cure!

Dementia may be common in older adults, but it's not a normal part of ageing. It's often caused by Alzheimer's disease or stroke. If it's a concern in your family, perhaps have a chat with your doctor to find out what lifestyle changes you can make to reduce your risk.

Whilst we may not completely understand the causes of Alzheimer's disease, we do know there is a link to some lifestyle risk factors of heart disease. These include physical inactivity, obesity, metabolic syndrome and decreased testosterone levels.

Gratitude is a simple, but an incredible superpower. Being grateful helps you develop a greater appreciation of others and the surrounding environment. This encourages individuals to value relationships more and foster stronger bonds. A good social support system creates a more positive outlook on life and provides opportunities for emotional unloading.

Prosocial skills include helping, cooperating, comforting and sharing. Psychologists believe these behaviours are best cultivated from a young age. These skills are linked with social competence, academic and career success. So what are you thankful for today?

Expressing gratitude to others can create a perception of friendliness, warmth and thoughtfulness to the receiver. Even if you're expressing gratitude to a stranger, it can cultivate a social bond between the two of you, and it might even prompt this stranger to respond with efforts to continue the relationship!

Who doesn't want a closer bond with their partner? Conveying gratitude indicates to your partner that you notice and recognise their contributions to the relationship. In response, they might be more appreciative and responsive towards you, leading to a nurturing relationship consisting of intimacy and commitment between both parties.
Sleep is not a luxury – it’s a critical foundation for a healthy lifestyle. Here are some tips to help you get better sleep.
contentWebLinkPreviewDescription: Many of the world’s major disasters happened purely because key decision makers were exhausted, so a good nights sleep is important to help us better manage our mood, to think clearly and stay focused.

contentDescription: Writing in a journal or app on your phone is a great way to practice gratitude. You can be grateful for anything - big or small, tangible or intangible. You can even appreciate the negative experiences in your past which have shaped you into who you are today! Don't worry if it feels unnatural at first, it will come more easily when practised consistently.

Research has shown participants who practised gratitude for three months became more sensitive to receiving and expressing gratitude. The study also found greater activity in learning and decision-making centres of the brain! As the brain becomes more sensitive to gratitude, improved mental health and well-being can also increase over time.

Research participants who practised gratitude reported better sleep quality and exercised up to 1.5 hours more than those who didn't practice gratitude. The surprising knock-on effects of gratitude are extremely beneficial to your physical wellbeing - not bad for something that requires minimal effort!

Being consistently appreciative can take you out of a negative rut. It opens a door to a broader perspective on the world, and focus on the positives in your life. What you're grateful for? It could be an experience, a person or your surrounding environment.

Organisations can benefit from the culture of gratitude. Studies have shown that managers who personally express gratitude to their employees, rather than generally towards their team, can see an increase in motivation and job satisfaction in the long run. Have you noticed that?

Did you know that exercise, meditation and yoga all stimulate the release of endorphins? Endorphins are hormones which make you feel good, protecting you from stress, hypertension, depression and heart attacks. They are also a natural painkiller, blocking pain signals from entering the brain. So give it a go!
Practising meditation promotes a relaxation response in our bodies. This physiological response is important to help balance out periods of stress we may experience in everyday life.

Mindfulness is the act of paying attention to your experiences in the present moment, like enjoying a cup of tea. This increases self-awareness, helping you respond positively to thoughts and adapt well to situations. Current research on daily mindfulness practice shows that apart from significantly reducing stress levels, it also reduces chances of burnout, depression and anxiety.

Research has found that listening to soothing music before or during a stressful event helps reduce your stress levels. Study participants who listened to soothing music showed a significant decrease in cortisol levels - the stress hormone - compared with those who skipped the music. Pretty interesting, right?!
We make about 60,000 decisions each day, and optimism helps us to respond wisely rather than react. Take these steps to stay optimistic even when times get tough.

contentDescription: Organisational psychologists found that employees who learnt new skills to supplement their workload were more resilient to stress. These skills provided a positive boost to their confidence, and along with their current abilities, aided in overcoming problems faced at work that gave rise to stress. Pretty cool!
Resilience is what keeps us in check when our emotions run wild or in stressful situations. Follow these tips to build on your resilience today!
contentWebLinkPreviewDescription: Resilience is the ability to “bounce back” from stressful or challenging experiences; it involves being able to adapt to changes and approach negative events, sources of stress and traumatic events as best we can. In this way we become our Better Self.

contentDescription: Who doesn't enjoy a warm bath to wind down? Did you know that it improves blood circulation and softens the joints, relieving pain and helping your muscles to relax? The buoyancy of the water decreases the impact of gravity on the body, which can also reduce physical tension and stress.
Practising self-compassion can protect you from unnecessary stress we can all sometimes impose on ourselves. Remember to be kind and love yourself.

Research has shown that humour promotes wellbeing and is an effective tool for stress management. People who laugh more are better equipped to cope with tough situations. They report feeling less tension, discomfort, and have a stronger immune system!

Having close friends and family who you can turn to in times of crisis are important. Research has found that individuals who have strong support systems manage stress and perform better in stressful situations! Social networks can provide you with emotional and physical comfort. Is it time to give a friend or family member a call?

Practising gratitude reminds you of the wonderful things - both big and small - that you appreciate in life. With all the hustle and bustle in our lives, it's easy to overlook the positives. When you're consistently grateful, you might just notice yourself being healthier, happier, more motivated and more resilient to stress.

Exercise is medicine. People who exercise regularly are protecting themselves from some of the negative emotional effects of stress. Research has found consistent exercisers are more emotionally resilient to stressful situations. Try for 30 minutes of exercise a day.

It’s easy to get sucked into this trap. If you're feeling under pressure, you are more likely to have a disrupted appetite, or you turn to unhealthy "comfort foods". Look for other ways to comfort yourself. A relaxing bath or a walk outside might do the trick.

Chronic stress activates the fight-or-flight system for a long time and can wear the body down. This may weaken the immune system and increase the risk of chronic diseases. So remember to plan fun or relaxing activities, so you can maximize the positive energy of stress without the long term side effects. :)

Prolonged stress can wear out your body and increase your risk of a weakened immune system, inflammation and heart disease. We don't want this happening to you, so go for a walk, read a book or any other activity that helps you unwind when you're feeling frazzled.

Oh dear, not a fun fact today. Addictive behaviours such as drinking alcohol, smoking, gambling and drug use can be triggered by chronic exposure to stress. Research suggests it can alter our motivation, self-regulation and emotional responses and, in turn, lead to a higher risk of developing addictive behaviours.

It’s important to be aware of the negative impacts of chronic stress so you feel motivated to positively manage your stress levels. Chronic stress has been associated with multiple health risks, including cancer. Scientists have found evidence that it can activate particular signalling pathways in cancer cells, which may result in the development of tumours.

Do you suffer from reflux, heightened sensitivity to different foods or even constipation? Stress can lead to adverse effects on your digestive system. Let’s make sure you plan fun activities into your week which help you laugh and relax.

Stress can have a detrimental effect on the human brain. Studies have found the part of the brain responsible for regulating memory, learning, motivation and emotions can be damaged by stress. The consequences can be similar to that of diseases such as Alzheimer's, Parkinson's and depression.

Scientists have found that the part of the brain responsible for your emotional responses can become over-stimulated and reactive after being exposed to long periods of stress. This can ultimately lead to a higher risk of feeling anxious or depressed. Sometimes a few deep breaths can help you feel relaxed if you're feeling frazzled.

It's common to experience acne breakouts when you're under stress. Research has found strong links between stress levels and acne severity, which could be explained by the hormonal imbalance stress causes in the body. This is just another reason to make time for self-care.

Chronic stress creates hormonal changes in both women and men, which may result in lower libido. Research indicates that prolonged and severe stress levels can physically affect testosterone levels in both men and women, resulting in lowered sex drives.

Scientists recently found a significant relationship between increased stress and decreased telomere length. Shorter telomere lengths predict a shorter life span. The take-home message is to look after your mental wellbeing to help aid your chances for a longer, happier life.

Stress has been linked with decreased motivation and an increased likelihood of developing depression. It's important to manage stress effectively to stay motivated and perform at your best. Remember, short term stress can be a positive to perform but make sure you practice ways that help you unwind.

People with a fixed mindset, view their character and abilities as inflexible and not within their control. This may cause fear when faced with difficult challenges or you're quicker to give up. Don't let a fixed mindset get in your way. Strive to be open and flexible to new experiences.

Anxiety is complex with many possible causes. To manage your anxiety well, it's important to have a thorough understanding of yourself and your environment. Forget about what you can't change and use tools that help you feel confident and in charge.

A rich economy is usually fast-paced. People in higher-income countries may encounter more stress due to intense competition and high expectations. In the pursuit of progress, it's important to look after your mental health to avoid burnout and maintain life satisfaction.

If you're ever feeling a bit anxious, keep in mind that there's a chance you might be misinterpreting the expression of others. Try to rely more on other cues and information to help avoid misunderstandings.

Next time you're feeling anxious, head out of a half-hour cardio session! You can go for a run, cycle, swim or any aerobic exercise of your choice. It'll help take the edge off, and keep you mentally sharper as well. A little daily exercise goes a long way.

Foods high in omega-3 fatty acids (e.g. oily fish and walnuts), probiotics (e.g. yoghurt and sauerkraut) and B vitamins (e.g. whole grains and dark leafy veggies) work to stabilise mood and regulate chemicals in the brain to ease anxiety symptoms. So add some mood-boosting food to your diet today!

Sometimes when suffering from depression, it's easy to feel alone. Remember that it's a common condition, and there are many avenues where you can seek help. If you, or someone close to you, is showing signs of depression, going to your family doctor is a great place to start.

If you are consuming more than 25% of your daily calories from added sugars, your risk of mortality from cardiovascular disease can almost triple! They're hiding in sauces, cereals, and marinades, as well as all the usual suspects. Look after your heart and reduce the amount of added sugar in your diet.

contentDescription: You are the only person that truly has to ability to change YOU. So let's grab life by the horns!
Make sure you walk the talk with the goals you're setting. :)

Don't look for hardship because you'll always find it. Try flipping your thoughts. For example, if you're stuck in traffic as the sun is going down, you could think, "Great, instead of enjoying this sunset, I'm stuck in a car", or, "Well, if I have to be stuck in a car, at least I get to admire this amazing sunset."
Why is your health important to you? Is it because you want to play with your kids? Have your dream holiday? Learn to surf? Think it, breathe it, live it. You deserve it!

If you want to improve your aerobic fitness, you might try jogging first, but then realise your knees hurt and you hate it. That's not failing; that's just eliminating one option. You might jump on a bike and love it. Experiment. Play. Learn. Figure out what works for you.

The importance of exercise has been known for a long time. Something is better than nothing, so even if exercise isn't part of your routine at the moment, try starting with 10 minutes a day. Already exercising? Find new and exciting ways to keep you engaged while challenging your body's fitness.
Health is a combination of physical, mental and social.

Exercise releases endorphins, which make you happy. Ensuring exercise is part of your daily routine is a great way to help improve your mood. As you become fitter, you may also notice your self-confidence improving. So here's a big thumbs up to exercise!
Good on you, Gandhi! It's important to invest in your health, so you can get the most out of life.

contentDescription: Sometimes, especially when going through a stressful period, it's hard to take time out for yourself. Remember to plan activities you enjoy and make enough time for a good 7-8 hours sleep.
Sometimes we seem to be waiting for a sign to start something, or to quit an old habit. No time is going to feel perfect, so you're best off just starting now. :)

Mindset is key! Starting something new can feel tough, but stuffing up is part of the process. Try not to see it as failure, but rather as learning and shaping how you're going to try again tomorrow, and the day after that.
How do you want to live your life? What are you doing now that's helping you hit your goals? What can you tweak to ensure you don't miss out? :)
Don't wait for a solution to your lifestyle choices to magically show up. Educate and empower yourself so you know what you need to do to become the best version of you possible.

Making changes to your health can be hard work. From the outside, people may notice you've lost weight, but that haven't seen how many times you chose to fight the urge to reach for a sugary snack, got up early to fit in a walk before work, or said no to after-work drinks so you could commit to an alcohol-free night. All those small moments and struggles are wins in their own right.

Thomas Edison held over 1,000 patents for different inventions, including the lightbulb and photographs. He knew a thing or two about hitting a roadblock! Don't be put off by your roadblocks. If you're trying to exercise more, and hate it when you go for a run, that's okay. There are many more forms of exercise to try. You've just crossed one off the list. Perhaps try swimming tomorrow. :)
Word! This is also part of work-life balance. Know how much your time is worth and invest it wisely.
Be your masterpiece! Invest time into eating right, moving regularly, connecting with friends and family and being kind to yourself.
Let's get creating!

If you put the effort in, you'll be rewarded. There are always going to be ups and downs, and improving your health and wellbeing isn't a steady ride. Make small commitments and stick to them. Just by cutting out sweetened drinks, for example, could help you lose weight. The choice is yours.

Forever can seem like a long time. Instead of setting yourself unattainable goals, aim for something smaller and more manageable. For example, 'I'm going to not have dessert for the next five nights'. Who knows, after the first five nights, perhaps the next five won't seem so daunting.

Exercise is a great example of this. If you want to push your fitness, you have to huff and puff or lift heavier weights than the time before. If it requires little effort, your body doesn't need to adapt or grow. You may even find that your fitness regresses instead.

Hope you're bathing daily! ;)  Don't expect to feel motivated every second of every day. Find your purpose and remind yourself of it. When your alarm goes off in the morning to go for a run, it can be a mental battle between getting up and hitting snooze. Remind yourself why you're choosing to exercise and make it meaningful to you.

What a great quote! If you want to see results, you have to invest time and effort. There are no magic pills or quick fixes. This doesn't mean you need to to do a complete overhaul.  Try changing a few things here and there, stick to it, and see how you go.

Don't let yourself be caught up with the wrong momentum. Be kind to yourself. Let's use quitting packet chips as an example: if you cave in to your cravings one day, try saying, 'That's okay, it's part of the process, and tomorrow I'm not going to give in'. And every time you say no to chips, count it as a win and celebrate it!

Sometimes previously unsuccessful attempts can make you nervous to give something a go in the future. But if you don't try, you can't succeed. Perhaps reflect on why it didn't work last time, and think about what has changed since then — and maybe try a different approach.
SMART Goals. Specific, measurable, achievable, realistic, and time-based Making a detailed plan is the best way to achieve your goal.

We speak about habits a lot. Practice doesn't make perfect, but it does make permanence. If you want to want to be an active person, you have to participate in activities daily, or a least almost daily. ;)

It's common to ask, 'What's better for me, running or cycling?'. The answer is the one you enjoy most. You might not like broccoli, but there are plenty of other greens out there you can eat to have a healthy diet. Make health fun and enjoyable for YOU.
You may set yourself a goal to run a four-hour marathon at next year's local event. But perhaps you run it in four hours and 10 minutes — that's still an incredible outcome and one worth celebrating.

Often we hear people saying, 'I don't exercise because it hurts my knees when I run.' That's okay, don't run. Try swimming, or cycling or do a yoga class. Or see an exercise physiologist and get a tailored plan just for you.
Don't let your own anger ruin your day. Take a breath, re-frame and move forward. :)

Only you can choose to be happy. If you wake up feeling a bit low, try faking it until you make it. Sometimes acting happy can make you happy. If you feel like you are struggling to feel happy regular, maybe it's time to chat with someone.
Often we place happiness on the other side of the cognitive horizon. 'I'll be happy when I've lost 10kg,' or 'I'll be happy when I get that promotion'. Enjoy the journey and appreciate the now. :)
Sometimes we can think that health is just what you eat and how active you are. Remember to make time with friends and family for a few belly laughs.
It's healthy to have a little perspective. Not every day can be amazing, but it gives us the ability to appreciate good moments when they happen.
It's no secret that eating healthy is a big component of being healthy. Avoid unnecessary illnesses and medication by feeding yourself with fresh foods full of nutrients, vitamins and fibre.
Right on! This doesn't mean you have to be super slim — just a healthy, happy you.

Sometimes health can take a back seat to other 'more important' priorities, like work deadlines or family needs. Your health is vital to ensure you can look after all those other essentials. You can manage stress more effectively, sleep better, have more energy to manage work and home life when you're taking care of your health.
Don't get lost in the rat race. Remember what's important. :)

Remember, you can treat yourself but it's about keeping it a treat. Try living by the 80:20 rule: if you do the right thing 80% of the time, don't worry about the occasional dirty burger, late night out or an extra drink or two. A balanced you is a happy you.
Bravo, Ralph! We agree!.
We know that's not the way it happens, and losing weight isn't easy. But choosing to make healthy choices every day will get you there, one step at a time.

It's hard to change habits, and doing the same thing you've always done is much easier.  Rather than maintaining the same lifestyle behaviours and taking medicines to counteract it, try investigating whether there are any lifestyle changes you can make to improve your health. You might be surprised by the power of good food and regular exercise.
Try not to be closed off to new ideas. Ideas for tweaking your current diet aren't an attack, but a way to help you take charge of your health and feel great.
It can be so tough to stay on course, but we know you can do it! :)
We agree, Morgan. There is no magic bullet. Healthy food can be delicious and exercising can be fun. Play, experiment and discover what works for you.
Do you get your car serviced regularly and take it to the mechanic when it's having trouble? How about doing the same for your body? It's your vessel for life, so show it some love. ;)
Don't let what 'could be' get the better of you! Enjoy who you are and what you have, and work on improving areas that could use a tweak.
In all seriousness, balance is the key to success. Don't burn yourself out by trying to do something at 110%. You need breaks, treats and rest days. Remember the 80:20 rule. :)
In all seriousness, balance is the key to success. Don't burn yourself out by trying to do something at 110%. You need breaks, treats and rest days. Remember the 80:20 rule. :)
The little moments matter just as much as the big ones. Don't forget to appreciate them. :)
Don't forget to laugh. It sends endorphins through your body, relaxes you and helps you manage stress.
Thanks Teddy! This is a great one to remember — don't forget to back yourself, you've got this!
This is a good quote for a not-so-good day. If not for yourself, then perhaps share it with a friend or family member when they're going through a tough time.
Life live to the fullest! Embrace your work, family and your health.
Failing is a part of the cycle of success. Throw your heart into what you care about. :)
You can always put things off for another day, but then you're no closer to reaching your goal.

Believe it or not, cardiovascular disease (commonly known as heart disease) is the number 1 cause of death in the developed world. High blood pressure is the most important risk factor to consider. Next time you visit your doctor, ask for your blood pressure to be checked.

Research has shown that just by reducing your blood pressure, your risk of stroke and coronary heart disease also reduces significantly. Exercise has been proven to be a fantastic non-pharmacological intervention to help reduce your blood pressure. Think about how you can add at least 30 minutes of exercise to your daily routine.

Magnesium helps the body break down sugars and may reduce the risk of insulin resistance (an inability to process glucose). Scientists are currently investigating whether magnesium supplements might help control type 2 diabetes, but more research still needs to occur in this space.
